<h4>Reporting Security Vulnerabilities</h4>
<p>We take security seriously. If you discover a security vulnerability in CasPaste, please report it responsibly.</p>

<h4>How to Report</h4>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Email:</strong> Send details to the security contact listed in our <a href="/.well-known/security.txt">security.txt</a> file</li>
	<li><strong>What to Include:</strong>
		<ul>
			<li>Description of the vulnerability</li>
			<li>Steps to reproduce the issue</li>
			<li>Potential impact assessment</li>
			<li>Any suggested fixes (optional)</li>
		</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<h4>What to Expect</h4>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Acknowledgment:</strong> We will acknowledge receipt within 48 hours</li>
	<li><strong>Assessment:</strong> We will assess the vulnerability and determine severity</li>
	<li><strong>Updates:</strong> We will keep you informed of our progress</li>
	<li><strong>Resolution:</strong> We aim to resolve critical issues within 30 days</li>
	<li><strong>Credit:</strong> With your permission, we will credit you in our <a href="/about/authors">acknowledgments</a></li>
</ul>

<h4>Scope</h4>
<p>This policy applies to:</p>
<ul>
	<li>The CasPaste server application</li>
	<li>The CasPaste CLI client</li>
	<li>Official Docker images</li>
	<li>Official documentation</li>
</ul>

<h4>Out of Scope</h4>
<ul>
	<li>Third-party hosted instances (unless operated by us)</li>
	<li>Social engineering attacks</li>
	<li>Physical security</li>
	<li>Denial of service attacks</li>
</ul>

<h4>Safe Harbor</h4>
<p>We consider security research conducted in accordance with this policy to be:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Authorized and legal</li>
	<li>Helpful to our security posture</li>
	<li>Exempt from legal action on our part</li>
</ul>
<p>We ask that you:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Act in good faith</li>
	<li>Avoid privacy violations and data destruction</li>
	<li>Do not exploit vulnerabilities beyond what is necessary to demonstrate them</li>
	<li>Give us reasonable time to address issues before public disclosure</li>
</ul>

